                'slug' => 'valorants-new-philippine-agent-neon-sparks-discussion-on-usage-of-filipinx-49577',
                'judul' => 'Valorant’s New Philippine Agent Neon Sparks Discussion on Usage of ‘Filipinx’',
                'deskripsi' => 'Valorant has quickly become one of Riot Games’ flagship franchises, with tons of fans around the world competing every day',
                'konten' => '<p>Valorant has quickly become one of Riot Games&rsquo; flagship franchises, with tons of fans around the world competing every day, streaming together, and even making all sorts of fan art featuring their favourite characters.</p>

<p>One of the reasons why the game strikes a chord with players from around the globe is the introduction of playable Agents from specific countries. And a newly announced character has become a massive treat for players in the Philippines.</p>

<p>Neon, the latest Agent in Valorant, is a Manila-based combatant with electricity-based powers. Classified as a duelist with a run-and-gun style of gameplay, Neon can sprint and slide her way into battle, and even create twin barriers to lock her enemies in place.</p>

<p>When it comes to crafting this Pinoy Agent, Riot Games have pulled all the stops to ensure an authentic and genuine Filipina character comes to life in their game. Every aspect of the character was taken into consideration, which really shows that representation goes a long way.</p>

<p>The journey began with Filipino Riot Games game designer Ryan Cousart, who designed Neon from scratch. Neon&rsquo;s voice actress, Vanille Velasquez, is also from the Philippines, and the reveal trailer for the character featured a song by Filipino-Australian singer, Ylona Garcia.</p>

<p>Needless to say, fans praised the great amount of effort poured into the character&rsquo;s reveal trailer. Who knows what other aspects of Neon will delight longtime fans when she is officially released.</p>

<p>However, Neon&rsquo;s reveal did cause some stir online. Some fans and media outlets referred to her as &lsquo;filipinx&rsquo;, a gender-neutral term used to describe people who hail from the Philippines.</p>

<p>This is similar to the term &lsquo;latinx&rsquo;, which is used to describelatinos and latinas. &lsquo;Filipinx&rsquo; may have been created in good faith but was ultimately rejected by Filipinos.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-02CyTd-6sXDULmBsdneru7E81dEDEk56-u8-JeXRhcctvlmh9u9mIsIShH_6w4dPo7TwrwfwzO9GxkPTlKYaTy-TA2T9EIZs1KWclij30nLyAcmQS5JE3batCJm_lw7TVF53zqQ" /></p>

<p>Some detractors said existing terms like Pinoy and Filipino are already considered gender-neutral. It&rsquo;s no surprise, then, that the use of the word &lsquo;filipinx&rsquo; reignited a debate between the East and West.</p>

<p>Such is the case with a now-deleted tweet by American esports host Erin Ashley Simon following Neon&rsquo;s reveal. She came under fire over the use of &lsquo;filipinx&rsquo;, which was intended to be a gesture of respect towards Filipinos.</p>

<p>Filipino Twitter users, however, lambasted the usage of &lsquo;filipinx&rsquo; in Simon&rsquo;s post, with many expressing their displeasure with the term. The term quickly became trending on Twitter, with over 2,800 Tweets from the Philippines alone.</p>

<p>In any case, Neon will be released as part of the huge Episode 4 Act 1 update for Valorant, which will be released on January 12.</p>',
